Dear all -

As many of you know, UAEM held our first National Day of Action on
Wednesday. I wanted to send a short wrap-up. Several of you on this
list spoke at events for the Day or leading up to it. We want to
express our thanks to you for helping to make it a great success.

We are still collecting news from all our chapters, but we believe
the day was a major stride in educating and motivating UAEM's fast-
growing student base. More than 40 chapters across the U.S., U.K.,
and Canada participated. Through the work of all these students, the
pressure on universities to take their rightful role in the access to
medicines battle is growing rapidly.

Summudles of many of the day of action events are up at http://
www.essentialmedicine.org/action. Many of our chapters have also
posted photos on our flickr group at http://www.flickr.com/groups/
uaem/. We'll be further updating these pages over the coming days. We
hope you will take a minute to look, and be inspired by the many
students who will become a generation of leaders in this fight.

We've also included below one representative story from our Yale
chapter's event, to give you a taste, as well as our press release
for the day.

Sincerely yours,

Michael and Robynn
Executive Directors
Universities Allied for Essential Medicines

> --------------------
> Students Protest High-Priced Pills
> --------------------
>
> By KIM MARTINEAU
> Courant Staff Writer
>
> April 19, 2007
>
> NEW HAVEN -- More than 10 million people die each year because they
> can't afford essential medicines, the World Health Organization
> estimates.
>
> Some of those drugs are discovered at American universities,  with
> public money, but by the time the drugs make it to market,
> they're  priced beyond reach of millions of people in poor  countries.
>
> Activists are calling on universities to help make their life-
> saving discoveries affordable to all. At Yale and dozens of  other
> campuses on Wednesday, students called on administrators  to
> rethink their licensing agreements with drug companies to
> increase  global access to medicines.
>
> At Yale, students left a pill bottle sculpture outside President
> Rick Levin's office. Made of 2,700 yellow pill bottles, it was
> meant to symbolize the 27,000 people who die each day for lack of
> medicine.
>
> "It's evocative," said law student Sarah Mehta, while threading
> wire through the bottles several nights ago in a machine shop on
> campus. "People have become desensitized to the numbers."
>
> The movement to expand access to medicines began at Yale six years
> ago, amid outrage that AIDS patients in Africa were dying as
> Bristol-Myers Squibb charged exorbitant prices for a drug developed
> at Yale, sold under the brand Zerit. Public pressure led the
> company to slash the price of Zerit and allow generic copies to be
> made.
>
> The victory led to the creation of a national advocacy group,
> Universities Allied for Essential Medicines, to persuade schools to
> negotiate low-cost medicines for poor countries when  striking
> licensing deals with drug companies.
>
> Last fall, a group of public health leaders - including four Nobel
> Laureates and the former editor-in-chief of the New England Journal
> of Medicine - signed a statement in  Philadelphia calling on
> universities to improve access to medicines and promote  research
> on neglected diseases.
>
> Last month, the Association of American Medical Colleges and 11
> universities, including Yale, responded with a statement of their
> own, affirming their obligation to help people suffering  from
> preventable or curable diseases. But they made no promises.
>
> That's a sticking point for activists. At Yale, more than two dozen
> drugs to treat cancer, HIV/AIDS and other illnesses are in the
> pipeline. Students want to make sure that when the drugs come to
> fruition, there will be allowances.
>
> "Every day that this remains just a set of principles on paper
> instead of concrete steps, there's a real human cost," said Michael
> Steffen, a Yale law student.
>
> Jon Ungphakorn, an AIDS activist and former Thai senator, spoke
> at  the law school Wednesday. It was his first stop on a tour  to
> protest Abbott Laboratories' recent withdrawal of seven new  drugs
> from Thailand, which came after Thailand threatened to  make a
> generic version of Abbott's anti-AIDS drug, Kaletra.
>
> Recently, Abbott announced it would cut the price of Kaletra by
> more than half but hasn't budged on its decision to keep some
> drugs off market.
>
> Ungphakorn wore a T-shirt with the words, "Worldwide Boycott
> Abbott." His American tour will culminate this month with a  stop
> at Abbott's annual shareholder meeting in Chicago.
>
> "It's important that universities show moral leadership," he
> said,  after snapping pictures of the pill bottle sculpture at
> Yale.  "It's very, very exciting seeing young students taking  the
> lead."
>
> In February, students met with Levin, an economist with  expertise
> in patents, to discuss their concerns. Law student  Shayna Strom
> faced his office Wednesday, her back to the pill  bottle sculpture.
>
> "President Levin, you have the power to be a leader on this  issue
> to make sure Yale's research goes to the public good,"  she said
> rhetorically, since it was clear Levin was nowhere to  be seen.
> "We  call on you to include access provisions in Yale's  licenses
> with  pharmaceutical companies - not some of the time,  for
> individual  drugs, but all of the time."
>
> Contact Kim Martineau at kmartineau@courant.com.
> Copyright 2007, Hartford Courant
>
>
> --------------------
> Visit www.courant.com for Connecticut news updates, sports
> stories, entertainment listings and classifieds.

