> National Day of Action Targets Universities in Fight for Global
> Access to Medicines
>
> PHILADELPHIA, Pa. As the fight for affordable AIDS treatment comes
> to a head around the world, with litigation in India, a showdown in
> Thailand, and heated debate in the U.S. Congress, a growing
> national student movement erupted on nearly 50 campuses today,
> demanding universities recognize their own role in the access
> crisis.  Students at top research institutions - including Harvard,
> U.C. Berkeley, and Johns Hopkins - joined a National Day of Action
> calling for lifesaving drugs developed in campus laboratories to be
> made available in the developing world.
>
> In recent months, universities have come under increasing pressure
> to ensure that the benefit of their biomedical research extends to
> the global poor. In November, more than 100 luminaries in medicine,
> law, and public health endorsed the “Philadelphia Consensus
> Statement,” calling for change at universities.  Meanwhile U.S.
> Senator Patrick Leahy (VT) introduced legislation that would
> mandate humanitarian licensing terms like those the Statement urged
> universities to adopt voluntarily.  On the heels of these
> developments, eleven leading universities publicly recognized their
> responsibility to ensure university research benefit the world’s
> poor . But, to date, not a single one has put the principle into
> practice for an actual drug with a global market.
>
> Thus, student activity reached a new pitch today with coordinated
> activity across the country. “There is now broad consensus that
> universities have a responsibility to ensure their research
> benefits people of all nations,” said Anna Weiss, a medical student
> at University of Pennsylvania,. “But we must move from rhetoric to
> action. Promising drug candidates continue to be licensed to
> pharmaceutical companies without any strategy for access to
> developing world patients.  Our message today is simple: Delay has
> a human cost.”
>
> To highlight that cost, Yale students constructed a haunting
> display of 2700 glowing pill bottles to commemorate the 27,000
> people that will die on the National Day of Action alone due to
> lack of access to existing medicines.  At Harvard, Dr. Jim Yong
> Kim, former World Health Organization HIV Director, called on
> students to engage their administrations to change policies, while
> at U.C. Berkeley, a conference of leading research scientists
> focused on ways to speed medical innovations from campuses to
> developing nations.
>
> “Universities can and must play a major role in alleviating the
> global access crisis.” said Dr. Kim, director of the François-
> Xavier Bagnoud Center for Health and Human Rights at the Harvard
> School of Public Health.  “As tightened patent protection under the
> World Trade Organization threatens the supply of affordable
> medicines, universities cannot stand idle while people are dying.”
>
> About Universities Allied for Essential Medicines
>
> Universities Allied for Essential Medicines (UAEM) is a coalition
> of students at over 35 research universities in the United States
> Canada, and the United Kingdom. In 2001, UAEM’s founders helped
> forge a deal between Yale and Bristol-Myers Squibb to lower the
> price of one of the most widely used AIDS drugs by 96% throughout
> sub-Saharan Africa.  The first major patent concession on an AIDS
> drug, the Yale/BMS deal helped create a tipping point for access to
> affordable AIDS treatment. UAEM has since worked to make such
> agreements a standard part of university licensing. The
> organization also works to promote university research on neglected
> diseases predominantly affecting those in impoverished countries.
> Please see http://www.essentialmedicine.org/action for more
> information.
